cycle‚Ää‚Äî‚Äägoing from a qualified lead to a closed deal. I presume you already have a good product and have found
product-market fit (or are close.) If this isn‚Äôt the case, there has been plenty written online about finding
product-market fit. I recommend starting
[here](https://www.amazon.com/Startup-Owners-Manual-Step-Step-ebook/dp/B009UMTMKS/190-7727698-9671318?ie=UTF8&btkr=1&redirect=true&ref_=dp-kindle-redirect).
This article is also not about prospecting or finding/identifying the right customers -- which is actually where you
should spend a large amount of your effort, so as not to waste time chasing dead ends.

<b id="footnote2">2</b> ‚ÄúTo programmers, 'hacker' connotes mastery in the most literal sense: someone who can make a
computer do what he wants‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääwhether the computer wants to or not.‚Äù‚Ää‚Äî [Paul Graham](http://www.paulgraham.com/gba.html)

<b id="footnote3">3</b> In this article I‚Äôm really talking about selling to large enterprise companies: Think
Fortune 500, high-touch complex sales with with lots of people involved; $1M+ deals. This is often called "elephant
hunting."

