## The Seven Questions

**1. What do you do?**  
Start with the name of your company and what it does. For example ‚ÄúSocialcam is a mobile app that makes it easy to take
videos and share them with friends and family.‚Äù There‚Äôs no need to set up the problem, you can just get to the point.

Too many people spend too much energy trying to make their idea sound impressive. It‚Äôs ok to keep it simple. Actually,
it‚Äôs preferable. You want to explain what you do in the simplest language possible. This needs to be predigested. Your
elevator pitch should be like baby food.

If you‚Äôre having trouble communicating your product simply, walking me through the user path can be an effective tactic.
For example, ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre Google. We build a website with a box in it. You can type any question into that box and we‚Äôll show
you websites that answer that question.‚Äù

Walking me through the user path helps avoid explanations like, ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre Google. We organize the world‚Äôs information by
indexing the web.‚Äù With that description I‚Äôm lost.

Your goal when answering this question should not be to have me understand your whole business but rather make me
interested enough to ask follow-up questions.

**2. How big is the market?**  
There are two ways to get market size. If you‚Äôre entering a pre-existing space (like small business banking) you can
research it. If you‚Äôre creating a new product or space (like Slack), you can estimate the number of customers that would
want your product and approximate how much you could charge them.

For example: Bellabeat makes an activity tracker for women. There are X women between 14 and 45 in the US. The lifecycle
of our activity tracker is two years. Our market opportunity in the US is Y.

When you‚Äôre estimating market size and what % you could own, there are two methods: top down and bottom up. With the top
down approach you determine the total market and estimate your potential share of it. With bottom up you figure out
where comparable products are sold, how many of them are sold, and what % of those sales you could take. I prefer the
bottom up method because it helps you avoid a common top down pitfall, which is not narrowing down the customer enough.
In the example above that could mean assuming all women are in your market - no matter their age or nationality.

**3. What‚Äôs your progress?**  
What I‚Äôm trying to understand here is how fast you produce work. What is the ratio between what you‚Äôve done and how long
you‚Äôve been working on it?

I want to feel impressed with how much you‚Äôve done in the period of time you‚Äôve had to do it. This can apply to a
company that‚Äôs one week old or ten years old.

I also tend to value product development and customers first and other things such as fundraising or biz dev deals a
distant second.

**4. What‚Äôs your unique insight?**  
This is similar to ‚ÄúWhat problem are you solving?‚Äù but the bar is higher. What I really want to understand is what you
know about the problem that everyone else doesn‚Äôt. This is usually derived from multiple conversations with customers,
deep analysis of current products in the space, and often personal experience.

For example: Gmail. A unique insight was that the email inbox is a personal database of communication and documents. Why
would a user ever want to delete anything in their personal database? Gmail gave people enough storage so they would
never have to delete a conversation. It‚Äôs not that people needed email. It already existed. And it‚Äôs not that people
needed better email. That‚Äôs too vague. A unique insight is specific and doesn‚Äôt contain complicated language.

Between your market and your unique insight, you have two opportunities to teach me something. A startup‚Äôs unique
insight often gives me more of an aha moment than the explanation of what the company does.

It‚Äôs worth noting that passion doesn‚Äôt help here. Saying a bad unique insight forcefully makes you look worse, not
better. For example, ‚ÄúDude, email today is fucking broken.‚Äù

**5. What‚Äôs your business model?**  
There are two types of startups, those that know how they‚Äôll make money and those that haven‚Äôt figured it out yet. By
and large, if you‚Äôre in the second category you‚Äôre going to either make money by growing big and turning on advertising
or you‚Äôre going to copy the predominant business model in your space. A small subset of companies in the second category
will propose a new business model that makes sense given how you product changes the market‚Äìfreemium is a good example
of this.

One mistake I often used to make at Justin.tv was offering a potpourri of business models (virtual goods, product
placement, chat ads, contests, etc..). I was embarrassed to say Justin.tv would monetize with advertising when clearly
that was the only answer. Own the simple business model.

**6. Who‚Äôs on your team?**  
I‚Äôm only interested in a few things: How many founders? Is there a technical co-founder? How long have they known each
other? Is everyone working full time? What is the equity split among the founders (hopefully equal or close to equal)?

If there‚Äôs an extremely relevant credential I also want to hear that. For example: You‚Äôre building a rocket company and
you used to be the rocket scientist for SpaceX. Basically, if you‚Äôre focusing on a deeply complex or regulated space,
having the expertise in house to plausibly tackle those problems is important.

You don‚Äôt need to mention your GPA or that you once worked at Google.

**7. What do you want?**  
There‚Äôs no need to dance around the ask. If you want me to invest, ask. If you have a question, ask. Though to be clear,
‚ÄúWhat do you think?‚Äù is a bad question. ‚ÄúDo I have a good idea?‚Äù is another bad question.

Make it easy for me to help you. I want to help you.

**Improving Your Answers**  
Once you have answers to each of the seven questions your challenge is to make the answers as clear as possible. To do
that you need to eliminate jargon, acronyms, marketing speak, and any ambiguous terms such as ‚Äúplatform‚Äù. Basically,
make it sound dumber than you think it should.

One tactic you can try is what I call ‚ÄúThe Email Test‚Äù. Write up a two sentence explanation of what your startup does
then email it to a smart friend. Ask them to explain it back to you in different words. If they ask any clarifying
questions, you need to revise your pitch. It‚Äôs important to do this over email because you can‚Äôt add explanations as you
would in conversation.

One thing we do during the YC batch that most people don‚Äôt realize is we help companies with their two sentence pitch.
The answer to the question ‚Äúwhat do you do‚Äù? We work on it every group office hours for the entire batch. It‚Äôs the
linchpin of a good demo day presentation. If that‚Äôs locked, writing a good demo day presentation is easy.

The real thing to remember when editing your answers is that you don‚Äôt need to sound cool. You need to be clear. Don‚Äôt
try to have pizzazz. You don‚Äôt want pizzazz.

**Conclusion**  
I‚Äôm much more interested in progress than genius ideas. Most good ideas don‚Äôt look like good ideas the first time you
see them so your ability to show progress in your work and intellect in how you answer these questions are two very
positive signals. Once I understand what you‚Äôre working on it‚Äôs all about making me believe that it‚Äôs plausible that you
can succeed.

