Ultimately, you should join a startup if learning trumps stability, if experience beats structure, and if building
things wins out over a steady paycheck. It doesn‚Äôt matter if the company succeeds or fails, when you join a startup
you‚Äôre going to gain knowledge and experiences that you will find nowhere else.

## **8.** **Frequently Asked Questions From Students**

**What Classes Should I Be Taking in College?**

There are no specific classes where you will learn to be a founder. Take courses you enjoy and work on projects that
interest you. These experiences will likely teach you more than anything in academia.

**Does it Matter What Degree I Have?**

Not really. If you enjoy coding, having a computer science or engineering degree is the best way to set yourself up for
success. If engineering is not something you want to focus on, college is a great place to find people who have skills
that are complementary to yours. That being said, if you want to run a software company, we recommend teaching yourself
the basics of coding, even if you‚Äôre not planning to be the CTO. Understanding how software works is a critical part of
building and running a technology company.

**What Skills Should I Be Learning?**

You don‚Äôt need to go to a specific school or have a specific degree to be a good founder. However, developing these
three skills in college will undoubtedly help in a career as a founder later on.

**Coding**

![](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/dhNFgnG94DxapBL-i1eqxxUZouAzus7XQLW6IpU0MZfMKJMovV_GIy6Pb36BRoU5xDtI34CO5TWc26ANIvATEVpjchOLw3CRO5x8fF7ou3P3yj_mGS3VjKk8MbL0lrnvCgWiGWgH)

Learn to code and become friends with technical folks. You can‚Äôt build a software enabled company without software.

**Communication**

![](https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/TUHPzjpmIj_VD7_rCY1kjvOkDCi3-Y9Jk-eSWq0HeQ-Jf1pw4qrAXlcjVI2G769U9LikGfw_xzGHwkZLICVntxqK47UEe3hKx2hBcJ0iezJBqTRmG4LT5B4WxfrpwtWkPA5ETJV2)

Learn to convey your ideas clearly and simply. Think of it this way: even if you‚Äôre working on something enormously
complex you have to be able to explain it in a way your grandparents will understand.

**People Skills**

![](https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/MK2XG11pYtcUCqJ6Sza-vZVQ5DZrYbrLStjiZHYgsYWEY_lLquPS3Kpfs630z1uhilvzX0FF0Cvq5CP7GVTXFjJe1WVlqZ2T8MBUCJiLhuQbBA4FNMIMtqqxXiiWt2VPDvrV-_TO)

Build your network. Meet potential co-founders. Gain a deeper understanding of what people's needs are. As a founder,
it‚Äôs crucial to talk to users so you can better solve their problems.

**How Should I Spend My Time at School?**

For most, college is a one time experience and we encourage you to enjoy it. It‚Äôs the ideal period to explore subjects
that fascinate you and find like minded people you enjoy working with.

College is one of the best places to meet a potential co-founder. Build your network and become friends with people who
you could potentially work with in the future.

Also, don‚Äôt forget that you also have access to the entire world. Experts in all kinds of fields ‚Äî technology, business,
science ‚Äî are usually happy to help college students.

For more advice on how to spend your time during university read [A Letter to College
Students](https://www.ycombinator.com/library/4d-a-letter-to-college-students) by Michael Siebel.

**Can I Still be a Founder Without a Technical Background?**

YC has funded some startups that don‚Äôt have a technical co-founder. Roughly ten percent of the companies in every batch
are founded by a non-technical founder. However, if you look at [YC‚Äôs Top
Companies](https://www.ycombinator.com/topcompanies) list you‚Äôll only see 3 companies founded by a non-technical
founder: Flexport, SnapDocs and UpKeep. If you are non-technical, we highly recommend finding a technical co-founder if
you‚Äôre building a software company. With someone technical on the team, you can move quickly and have a greater chance
of success.

**How Do I Meet a Cofounder?**

The most common way people meet their co-founders is through school and work. We looked at the top performing YC
companies to see how the founders connected with each other. Here‚Äôs the breakdown:

**YC‚Äôs TOP COMPANIES (68 entries)**

![](https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/o70IyTyNiSwa98gw4Lk9q_uUqpn5vn7IM2J0ESg7wpEDJFoFSi4XPQqiJTvNn3ai0FJhZTUr7NIQcHlIdi4NnZY-Z9FimJsJwJDRtP2LNSWoRijjjJ3T00YYktZgSHrv0Li3YwoE)

We also looked at how women met their co-founders \>\>

**WOMEN FOUNDERS (78 entries)**

![](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/Z3VuGGyhRZzxYr0mZ9IHKz24itS2V32i2AYX_yklggg6SZwf4v6omutJfzWhWT3Rc5H_z-XTvoUKHN1YSSLzItJIJIYFHCQkKEe48rF2PWxyycnsSUc4sjGggknMMSk9GyJCiwIy)

\**A good way to get started is working on projects or extracurricular activities with your classmates.*

YC‚Äôs Startup School also recently launched a [co-founder matching
platform](https://www.startupschool.org/cofounder-matching). We pair you with co-founders based on your preferences for
interests, skills, location, and more. While we don‚Äôt suggest you immediately start a company with someone you meet on
this platform, it is a great way to connect with like-minded people who are interested in starting a company. You still
need to do the hard work of building a strong, trusting relationship.

For more on transforming a school project into business, read [From Student Side Project to
Startup](https://www.ycombinator.com/library/6A-from-student-side-project-to-startup) by Paul Dornier co-founder of
[Meetingbird.](https://www.ycombinator.com/companies/meetingbird)

**How do I decide on the idea?**

When landing on a concept for a startup, keep these three items in mind. But as we‚Äôve said before, ideas can easily be
changed.

<ul padding-left: 15x;> <strong>1.</strong> Intention matters <br> We‚Äôve found the best YC founders are solving problems that they or a loved one have personally faced. Think about why you want to solve the problem you‚Äôre solving. Will you care about it a decade from now? <br> <br> <strong>2.</strong> Don't follow the mainstream <br> Doing something because it‚Äôs considered ‚Äúcool'' will likely not be successful. When Coinbase was founded in 2012, cryptocurrencies were very much a fringe idea. Today it‚Äôs pretty likely your grandmother has heard of Bitcoin. <br> <br> <strong>3.</strong> Solve for needs <br> It‚Äôs tricky to balance an understanding of what people want versus what they need. Focus on what people are actually willing to spend their time or money on, not just what they say they want. <br> <br> For more, watch <a href=https://www.ycombinator.com/library/6G-how-to-build-the-future>How to Build the Future with YC‚Äôs Sam Altman</a>. <br></ul>

**I‚Äôve built something. How do I get my first users or customers?**

<ul padding-left: 15x;> <strong>1.</strong> College campus. <br> A great part of being on a college campus is that you have easy access to a large pool of potential customers who are likely to try something new. <br> <br> <strong>2.</strong> Friends and family. <br> Ask everyone you know ‚Äì aunts, grandparents, cousins, friends, acquaintances ‚Äî to use your product. This will help you determine your ideal demographic. <br> </ul>

**Should I charge for my product?**

Charge for your product as soon as possible. The amount doesn‚Äôt need to be very much, but charging will help you
understand how much value you‚Äôre creating and how much people are willing to spend on what you‚Äôre building.

**How do I convince my parents that starting a startup is a smart idea?**

Share stories of successful young founders. John and Patrick Collison were 19 and 21 respectively when they started
Stripe. Alex Rodrigues of Embark Trucks was just 19 when he founded his company.

Inform them how startup experience is valuable, even if the company fails. There will always be corporate jobs and many
YC founders join big companies when their startups shutter.

Also remind them startups are easier when you‚Äôre younger. It‚Äôs true you can start a startup at any age, but when you
have lots of energy and little commitments, it‚Äôs much easier to spend time building.

**Should I finish my degree or dropout and pursue my startup?**

We tell most students to finish their degree. But if the only thing you can do is think about your startup and you‚Äôre
spending all your free time working on it, it might be worth considering dropping out.

